The divorce rates statistic is often regarded as an indicator of the failure of the institution of marriage and, as such, feminists tend to bemoan such a 'seeming' insignificance. This disdain is odd, because after all, the truth is that gender equality stems directly from the advances in legal policy of equal access to the individual's entitlements and privileges. Divorce should not be seen as a failure of marriage, but rather as an option that preserves the rights of couples when those institutions cease to function. In that vein, women do not get divorced 'just cause.'

For both of these reasons, the Church of Transformation is very insistent on sensibly competitive behaviors between women. They mock the topics of envy, pity, cajoling, envy, resentment, shame, and all of these negative emotions. They are quite insistent on planting a seed of a competitive spirit, teaching women to be fair, and taking the authority to avoid situations and people that choose to treat them unfairly. For the reasons above, it is mandatory that women know that their rights (both in The Bahamas and abroad) arising from the Contracts Act 2000, explicitly state that women are entitled to equitably maximize their relationship while in it.
